    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-08-27T12:50:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-08-27T12:50:00-05:00" n="301"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d301">
                <head>301. Memorandum of Telephone Conversation Between the Under Secretary of State
                    for Political Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_HWA1" type="from"
                        >Harriman</persName>) and the Assistant Secretary of State for Far Eastern
                    Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_HR1" type="to">Hilsman</persName>)<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d301fn1">Source: Library of Congress, <persName
                            corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> Papers, Telephone Conversations.
                        Transcribed by Dolores P. Perruso of <persName corresp="#p_HWA1"
                            >Harriman</persName>’s staff.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <hi rend="italic">
                            <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                                type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1963-08-27T13:50:00-04:00"
                                >August 27, 1963, 1:50 p.m.</date>
                        </hi>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HR1">Hilsman</persName> said he thought he could bring
                        <persName corresp="#p_NFEJ1">Nolting</persName> around.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> asked if some people were
                    getting cold feet.</p>
                <pb facs="0684" n="658" xml:id="pg_658"/>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HR1">Hilsman</persName> said he was afraid of <persName
                        corresp="#p_TGMD1">Maxwell Taylor</persName>. He said we have to make this
                    work. <persName corresp="#p_HR1">Hilsman</persName> said he was going to the
                    Hill and thought the Governor should be available to go to the White House.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> said I hope you won’t let them
                    spoil the image of the US.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
